name: Big Rock Campbell River
description: Located on shoreline near south end of Campbell River, Georgia Straits, Vancouver Island. Sits on beach as prominent coastal landmark. Transported by ice sheet 3-4 km thick.
cultural_significance: "Indigenous folklore describes it as boastful grizzly bear turned to stone. Explains absence of grizzly bears on Vancouver Island. Community message board for millennia."
historical_notes: "Decorated with painted messages as community expression canvas. Featured in digital cultural mapping project [https://www.campbellrivermirror.com/entertainment/get-interactive-with-campbell-rivers-big-rock-1451833]. Town named after geological landmark."

name: Bellevue Erratic / Sheridan Erratic
description: Located on 250-foot hill in Yamhill Valley between Sheridan and McMinnville. Largest glacial erratic in Willamette Valley, only rock of its type outside Canada.
cultural_significance: "Educational and recreational site in wine country. Nearly closed 1996
column12: new marker installed 2005. State park with interpretive signage and picnic facilities."

name: H Street Erratic
description: Located 0.5 miles east up H Street hill from WA 543 in Blaine. Rounded conglomerate boulder on private property, visible from roadside.
historical_notes: "Reported by resident to geologist Dave Tucker. Featured in Northwest Geology Field Trips blog."

name: Willamette Meteorite
description: Both a meteorite and a glacial erratic, the Willamette Meteorite was transported and positioned by glacial action during the Missoula Floods approximately 13,000 years ago. Weighing 15.5 tons, it is the largest glacial erratic found in North America and shows distinctive sculpting from both its fiery passage through Earth's atmosphere and subsequent glacial transport across the Pacific Northwest landscape.
cultural_significance: "Sacred to the Confederated Tribes of Grand Ronde
image_url: who called it 'Tomanowos' and considered it a spiritual mediator between earth and sky. The meteorite's extraterrestrial origin combined with its glacial repositioning creates a unique intersection of cosmic and terrestrial geological processes
column12: making it significant to both indigenous cosmology and modern scientific understanding."
column13: "Discovered by European-American settler Ellis Hughes in 1902
column14: leading to a legal battle over ownership between Hughes and the Oregon Iron and Steel Company. The meteorite was eventually acquired by the American Museum of Natural History in New York
column15: though the Grand Ronde tribes have ongoing cultural connections to it. Recent efforts focus on collaborative stewardship that honors both scientific and indigenous perspectives."

name: Lake Stevens Monster Erratic
description: Among the largest glacial erratics in the United States, this massive serpentinized greenstone boulder measures 78 feet long, 54 feet wide, and 34 feet high with a 210-foot circumference. The rock is composed of 125-million-year-old metamorphosed seafloor basalt transported approximately 37 miles from near Whidbey Island by the Vashon Glacier. Hidden in a residential neighborhood, it sits in a small park maintained by Glen Acres Homeowners Association.
historical_notes: ' this geological treasure remained relatively obscure despite its massive size until formal documentation in 2011. The boulder has attracted some climbing activity over the years and increasingly draws geological enthusiasts aware of its potential status as America's largest erratic. Its location in a 1990s subdivision reflects the intersection of suburban development with significant geological features."
column12: the erratic was first scientifically documented and measured in 2011 by Lake Stevens police officers Craig Valvick and Matt McCourt. At 11 feet taller than Madison Boulder
column13: it is among the largest erratics in the US. The rock's composition of ancient seafloor lava subjected to metamorphism tells a complex geological story spanning 125 million years. Despite its significance
column14: it remained largely unrecognized by the broader geological community until recent documentation efforts."

name: Big Rock Okotoks
description: Known as Okotoks Erratic, this massive quartzite boulder near Calgary, Alberta, is the largest glacial erratic in the world, weighing approximately 16,500 tons. The boulder was transported over 400 kilometers from the Canadian Shield by the Laurentide Ice Sheet during the last glacial maximum. Its imposing presence on the Alberta prairie makes it visible from great distances and has served as a landmark for countless generations.
historical_notes: who call it 'Okotok' meaning 'rock' in Blackfoot language. Traditional stories describe it as a sleeping giant or as a piece of the sacred landscape that the Creator placed to mark important territories. The boulder represents the connection between geological and spiritual time scales
image_url: embodying the Blackfoot understanding of landscape as animated and meaningful."
column12: "Used as a landmark by indigenous peoples for thousands of years before European contact. Early European explorers and fur traders also used it for navigation across the prairie. The town of Okotoks was named after the boulder
column13: and it remains central to local identity. Modern geochemical analysis has traced its origins to the Athabasca region
column14: demonstrating the immense power of glacial transport."

name: Balance Rock
description: Massive marble erratic precariously balanced on smaller bedrock in Pittsfield State Forest. Appears to defy gravity with small contact point.
cultural_significance: "Major tourist attraction for Berkshires since 1800s. Featured on postcards and promotional materials for western Massachusetts tourism."
historical_notes: "Weathering forces worn away supporting material creating dramatic balancing appearance. Protected within state forest system."

name: Rollstone Boulder
description: Originally on Rollstone Hill summit, 110-ton erratic moved to downtown Fitchburg 1929. White feldspar phenocrysts indicate origin from central New Hampshire ridges.
cultural_significance: "Landmark for Native Americans and settlers for centuries. Tourist attraction in late 1800s. Symbol of Fitchburg with businesses named after it."
column12: moved piece by piece and reassembled at traffic island. Process meticulously documented with numbered pieces."

name: Madison Boulder
description: New Hampshire's largest glacial erratic, this 5,000-ton Placeholder rock type boulder measures 83 feet long and 37 feet high. Located in Madison, New Hampshire, the boulder was transported approximately 2 miles from its bedrock source by glacial action during the Wisconsin glaciation. Its massive size and prominent position make it one of the most impressive examples of glacial transport in New England
cultural_significance: "Long recognized by the Abenaki people as a significant landmark in their traditional territory. The boulder's impressive scale has made it a symbol of New England's glacial heritage and the immense power of ice age forces. Modern visitors often comment on the humbling experience of standing beside such a massive object moved by natural forces
historical_notes: reflecting on both geological time and human temporality."
image_url: "Noted by early European settlers and featured in local folklore and early geological surveys of New Hampshire. The boulder has been protected as a state natural area since 1948
column12: making it one of the first glacial erratics to receive formal preservation status. Recent educational programs use the boulder to teach about glacial geology and climate change
column13: connecting past ice ages to contemporary environmental challenges."

name: Rolling Rock
description: Located at County and Eastern Avenue intersection on traffic island. Previously could rock/roll but stabilized. Designated Massachusetts State Glacial Rock 2008.
cultural_significance: "Subject of 25-year preservation battle (1905-1930). Official state glacial rock through Wixon School student advocacy 2008. Legend claims Native American torture use."
historical_notes: "City acquired land 1930 after preservation campaign. Plaque commemorates preservation. One of few erratics with official state designation."

name: Dighton Rock
description: A 40-ton sandstone boulder covered with petroglyphs, located along the Taunton River in Massachusetts. The rock bears hundreds of markings including faces, animals, geometric patterns, and possible script that have sparked centuries of debate about their origins. Geological analysis indicates the boulder was transported by glacial action during the Pleistocene epoch, coming to rest in its riverbank position as ice sheets retreated.
cultural_significance: "The petroglyphs represent multiple periods of indigenous artistic expression
historical_notes: with the earliest markings potentially dating back 8
image_url: 000 years. Various groups including the Wampanoag
column13: and even Vikings have been credited with the inscriptions. The rock serves as a palimpsest of cultural contact
column14: with layers of meaning accumulated over millennia of human interaction with this glacial monument."
column15: "Documented by European colonists as early as 1680
column16: with sketches made by numerous scholars and antiquarians. The rock was moved in 1963 to Dighton Rock State Park to protect it from industrial development and river erosion. Recent archaeological work has employed 3D scanning and photogrammetry to create detailed records of the markings before further weathering occurs."

name: Plymouth Rock
description: A glacial erratic boulder located in Plymouth, Massachusetts, traditionally identified as the landing site of the Mayflower Pilgrims in 1620. While geological evidence suggests the boulder was deposited during the last glacial period approximately 20,000 years ago, its symbolic significance in American colonial history has made it one of the most famous erratics in North America. The boulder is composed of Dedham Granodiorite, matching bedrock found 15 miles to the south.
cultural_significance: "Sacred to the Wampanoag people long before European colonization
historical_notes: Plymouth Rock became a powerful symbol of American origins and the Pilgrim narrative. The boulder represents both geological deep time and the compressed mythology of American founding. Its transformation from anonymous glacial deposit to national shrine illustrates how natural objects acquire cultural meaning through human interpretation and ritual practice."
image_url: "First identified as the Pilgrims' landing site in 1741 by Thomas Faunce
column12: nearly 120 years after the supposed event. The boulder was moved multiple times
column13: broken in 1774 during an attempt to relocate it
column14: and has been housed in various memorial structures. Modern DNA analysis of the Wampanoag community reveals continuous occupation of the region for thousands of years before European contact."

name: Babson Boulders
description: ~24 large Placeholder rock type erratics across Dogtown Commons. During Great Depression, millionaire Roger Babson hired unemployed Finnish stonecutters to carve inspirational messages.
cultural_significance: "Inscribed boulders serve as outdoor inspirational messages. Unique Depression-era public works project. Messages include 'Keep Out of Debt'
column14: later donating to Gloucester. Carving project employed 35 workers in 1930s. Babson saw this as 'book written in stone'."

name: Doane Rock
description: Largest exposed glacial erratic on Cape Cod, between Salt Pond Visitor Center and Coast Guard Beach. Shows glacial polish and rounding. Accessible via short trail.
historical_notes: early Plymouth Colony settler. Popular climbing and picnic destination. Featured in Cape Cod National Seashore programs."
column12: and 'Great Rock' historically. Transported by Laurentide Ice Sheet from Massachusetts Bay region."

name: Kidston Lake Rocking Stone
description: Large Placeholder rock type boulder in Kidston Lake Park that can be rocked with leverage, transported by glacier from bedrock northwest. Halifax Regional Municipality heritage property 2022
historical_notes: attracted visitors 200 years including potential royal visitors. Site of community gatherings and picnics since early 1800s."
image_url: "First scientifically described by Rev. David Honeyman 1880s as glacial erratic. Lost some rocking ability after Halifax Garrison soldiers rocked it vigorously 1890s."
